url.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSpeaking for the growing community of Latina feminist theologians, the editors of this volume write, "With the emergence and growth of the feminist theologies of liberation, we no longer wait for others to define or validate our experience of life and faith. We want to express in our own words our plural ways of experiencing God and our plural ways of living our faith. And these ways have a liberative tone." With twelve original essays by emerging and established Latina feminist theologians, this first-of-its-kind volume adds the perspectives, realities, struggles, and spiritualities of U.S. Latinas to the larger feminist theological discourse. The editors have gathered writings from both Roman Catholics and Protestants and from various Latino/a communities. The writers address a wide array of theological concerns: popular religion, denominational presence and attraction, methodology, lived experience, analysis of nationhood, and interpretations of life lived on a border that is not only geographic but also racial, gendered, linguistic, and religious.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aFeminist theology. 0aHispanic American womenxReligious life. 0aMujerista theology. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / Catholic.2bisacsh1 aAdams, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAquino, María Pilar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAquino, María Pilar, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDelgado, Teresa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGonzález, Michelle A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuardiola-Sáenz, Leticia A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLoya, G